ough six distinct phases: birth, formation, display, dispersal, construction, and return. By following the life of steel from the collection of raw minerals to the distribution and disposal of finished products, Christensen challenges the traditional narrative that steel was simply the primary material responsible for architectural modernism.Based on the premise that building materials are as much a part of the natural world as they are of a building, this groundbreaking book rewrites an important chapter of architectural history. It will be welcomed by specialists in architectural history, nineteenth-century studies, environmental history, German studies, modernist studies, and the Anthropocene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArchitecture, Moderny19th century. 0aBuilding, Iron and steelxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradexEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradexHistoryy19th century. 0aSteel industry and tradezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076692940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271092454?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271092454/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK